{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778768772,"nonce":"zQZb7s55Dni7GKwpIdq+b5qO3Mc=","title":"This is **v2** of the implementation plan for the decisive cs2019-induction experiment. It **supersedes v1 at `35f64be`** (see `35f64be` comment `355ff46` for the full Codex critique). v1 remains open as the historical v1 record per the issue closure policy; no commits should reference v1 as a `Bug:` trailer.","message":"This plan operationalises the synthesis at `0b1f109`: cs2019's analytical game is full-state ε H∞ (per `0b1f109` comment `0cbb19f`'s Eq 9 → Eq 10 math), and the humans whose behaviour cs2019 fits are interpreted as adopting a *broad-defense policy* against an admissible class strictly larger than any single curl field they faced (per `0dbf19f`). The training game we operationalise here matches that analytical specification.\n\n**Scope of v2 changes vs v1**:\n\n- 7 OPEN questions resolved per Codex's recommendation (`355ff46`); only 2 residuals carried forward.\n- New **Phase 0.5 — Analytical target materialization** inserted before any implementation. Cost-schedule choice subsumed into it (it is part of game specification, not a phase).\n- Phase 1 (adversary class) gated by a **pre-implementation feedbax state-map specification + regression test**, which Codex flagged as blocker-level.\n- Phase 3 success criterion rewritten as a **multi-criterion same-game certificate** (K match + nominal trajectory match + LQR warmup sanity + robustness match + Δv match within absolute band + overshoot fail rule), replacing the v1 \"Δv \u003e +1% with CI overlap\" sign-only test.\n- Phase 4 GRU decision tree explicitly enumerates the three outcomes from `08b41df` (couples / dissociates / partially couples), and points to `0bbd1ef`'s Path 1 / Path 2 contingency, with Codex's preference for Path 1 (biomechanical) over Path 2 (architectural restriction) flagged.\n- New **\"What comes after Phase 4\" section** carrying the 5-stage bridging chain from `01b512f` (Gate → Bridge 1 plant → Bridge 2 targets → Bridge 3 delayed-reach → Interpretability), with epoch-gating constraint for the ε adversary in Bridge 3.\n\n---\n\n\nIssue child: `b6084c7`.\n\nCheap, no-new-training. Runs against existing checkpoints. The audit must produce `results/b6084c7/notes/2026-05-12_trajectory_cost_audit.md` and verify, for each of the four existing controllers (baseline GRU `f47abb1` `lit__post_nojerk` warmup-only winner; flavor-B GRU from `c723082`; trained LTV regulator from `410d7ac` `linear_regulator__adversarial`; analytical Riccati from `cs_faithful_pointmass`):\n\n- Plant config: damping, τ, mass, dt, state dim, delay handling\n- Cost: Q schedule shape, R, terminal cost, horizon\n- Adversary class actually optimised against\n- Task input channels (target_pos, target_vel, hold flag, target_on, SISU)\n- Loss-term breakdown active during training\n- Catch-trial probability\n\nOutput: side-by-side table flagging every axis on which the four controllers differ. **The audit can run in parallel with Phase 0.5 and Phase 1 design, but Phase 1 training is gated on the audit table being present.**\n\n---\n\n\nThe gate is \"same H∞ game,\" not \"positive Δv.\" That requires writing down the contract — the exact analytical solution the trained linear arm must match — *before* implementing the training pipeline. Codex: *\"write out the exact cs_faithful LQR/H∞ trajectories, K_t, γ*, chosen γ, worst-case ε*, its norm, nominal Δv, induced gain, and cost time courses. This artifact is the contract the trained linear arm must match.\"*\n\n**Plant + game specification** (fixed for the gate; not parametrised):\n\n- `plant = cs_faithful_pointmass()` — mass=1, k=0.1 Ns/m, τ=0.066 s, dt=0.01 s, `disturbance_integrator=True`, `delay_steps=5`. Augmented state dim **n = 48** (8 phys + 5·8 lag). `B_w = I_48` analytically.\n- `schedule = apply_delay_distribution_to_schedule(cs_eq15_cost_schedule(n_steps=60, state_dim=8), delay_steps=5)`. R = I_2.\n- Horizon T = 60 steps × 0.01 s = 0.6 s. Hold-free, movement-only. No catch trials. No go-cue input.\n- Canonical reach: 15 cm forward (single direction). Mixed directions are a Bridge 2 concern, not the gate.\n- Game: free time-varying full-state ε_t ∈ ℝ^48 per step; budget `∑_t ‖ε_t‖² ≤ E` (rollout-integrated L2; no per-step cap).\n- Cost-schedule decision lives here, not as a standalone phase: cs_eq15 `(t/N)^6` is what defines this game (`6ec6b19` folded in).\n\n**Artifacts to produce** (committed under `results/b6084c7/notes/cs_faithful_analytical_target.md` or a sibling note):\n\n1. γ* via `find_gamma_star(plant, schedule)`; chosen γ = 1.5 γ*.\n2. Riccati K_t* time series (T × 2 × 48) at γ → ∞ (LQR limit) and at chosen γ (H∞).\n3. Nominal trajectory x_nom(t) under each: peak forward velocity, time-to-peak, terminal position error.\n4. Worst-case ε*_t trajectory at chosen γ, its rollout-integrated L2 norm `E_riccati = ∑_t ‖ε*_t‖²`. **This is the budget E for the trained adversary** (Codex Q6 resolution).\n5. Nominal Δv = (peak v_fwd at γ chosen) / (peak v_fwd at γ → ∞) − 1 (the analytical signature the training must reproduce).\n6. Cost time course `x_t^T Q_t x_t` and `u_t^T R u_t` under each.\n7. Induced full-state ε gain `γ_net(K*)`, computed via the analyser in `induced_gain.py` (or hand-derived).\n\n**Optional bridge artifact (non-gate)**: produce the same artifacts for the production plant (k=10, τ=0.05 s, n_steps=60, hold-free) with cs_eq15 schedule, marked *\"not a training gate, Phase 0.5 production-plant reference for Bridge 1.\"* Codex's recommendation in `355ff46`.\n\n**Outputs (committed)**:\n\n- `results/b6084c7/notes/cs_faithful_analytical_target.md`: prose + tables for the cs_faithful target.\n- `results/b6084c7/notes/production_plant_analytical_reference.md` (optional, marked non-gate).\n- Numerical artifacts under `_artifacts/b6084c7/analytical_target/` (`.npz`s for K_t, x_nom, ε*).\n\n---\n\n\n\n**Before any code lands**: specify the exact state-map from ε ∈ ℝ^48 to feedbax StateIndex leaves to analytical `B_w` rows. cs_faithful's analytical state is delay-augmented (48D) — a post-Mechanics intervenor that mutates only effector/plant state will NOT implement `B_w = I_48`. The state-map must cover:\n\n- Physical effector state (px, py, vx, vy, fx, fy) → which `MechanicsState` leaves?\n- Disturbance-integrator states (eps_x_int, eps_y_int) → integrator hook? Or augmented separately?\n- Delay-lag buffer (5 × 8 lag states) → are these visible to the controller via the sensory channel? Are they materialised in feedbax at all, or only implicit in the simulator's history? If implicit, the analytical `B_w = I_48` requires *materialising* the lag chain on the feedbax side so ε_t can shift it.\n\n**Specification artifact**: a note at `results/b6084c7/notes/feedbax_state_map.md` (or sibling) with a 48-row table:\n\n| ε index | Analytical state | feedbax StateIndex path | Hook |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 0 | px | `mechanics.effector.pos[0]` | post-Mechanics direct |\n| ... | ... | ... | ... |\n| 6 | eps_x_int | `\u003cintegrator\u003e` | TBD |\n| 7 | eps_y_int | `\u003cintegrator\u003e` | TBD |\n| 8 | px(t−1) | `\u003cdelay buffer block 1, slot 0\u003e` | TBD |\n| ... | ... | ... | ... |\n| 47 | fy(t−5) | `\u003cdelay buffer block 5, slot 5\u003e` | TBD |\n\n**Regression test gate**: a unit test under `tests/test_full_state_epsilon_adversary.py` (or feedbax equivalent) that, with **zero control and a known ε basis vector e_i**:\n\n- Runs one simulation step.\n- Asserts: the state coordinate corresponding to ε index i changed by exactly ε_i (or `dt · ε_i`, depending on the discrete-update convention chosen — this convention must match the Riccati's discrete-time `x_{t+1} = A x_t + B u_t + ε_t`).\n- Asserts: an empirical linearisation `(x_{t+1} − A x_t − B u_t) / ε_t` recovers `B_w = I_48` row by row.\n\nIf delay-buffer states cannot be cleanly mutated through a feedbax intervenor, the alternative is to **rebuild the Riccati target with a different state structure** (e.g. drop delay augmentation, use the 8-state form) — but that changes the analytical Δv from ~+7–8% to a different number and must be re-derived in Phase 0.5. **Block Phase 1 training launch until the state-map note + regression test exist and pass.**\n\n\nThe PGD projection budget `∑_t ‖ε_t‖² ≤ E` uses a raw Euclidean norm over the 48 augmented state coordinates. The Riccati's `γ² ε^T ε` metric uses the same norm. Verify by inspection that state scaling is consistent across:\n\n- `cs_eq15_cost_schedule` (analytical Q, which scales Q by `[1.0e6 on pos, 1.0e5 on vel]`).\n- feedbax `MechanicsState` leaves (which are unit-scale physical quantities).\n- The PGD projection (which sees `ε.flatten()` and computes Euclidean L2).\n\nIf any scaling differs, the trained adversary's budget is a different game from the Riccati's worst case. Document the scaling check in `feedbax_state_map.md`.\n\n\n`FullStateEpsilonAdversary` in `src/rlrmp/adversary.py` (capability-named per CLAUDE.md script-placement rules):\n\n- Storage: `epsilon: Float[Array, \"T n\"]` directly on the `eqx.Module`. T = 60, n = 48.\n- Time-varying, free, per-step. ε_t is a function of `t` only (open-loop adversary), not of state — matching the Riccati formulation where the worst-case ε*_t is an open-loop trajectory once optimised.\n- **Budget**: rollout-integrated L2 only, `∑_t ‖ε_t‖² ≤ E` (Codex Q2 resolution; per-step caps deferred as a different adversary class).\n- **Default E**: Riccati worst-case ε*_t rollout-integrated norm at the chosen γ (Codex Q6 resolution). Single value, calibrated from Phase 0.5.\n- Projection: rescale the full (T·n)-flat vector if its L2 norm exceeds √E; otherwise pass through (single norm + `jnp.minimum`-based scale, analogous to `_frobenius_project` in `LinearDynamicsAdversary`).\n- **SISU coupling**: budget at SISU=1 is `E`; at runtime scale by SISU via the intervenor's `params.scale = SISU` field (same pattern `LinearDynamicsAdversary` uses, `src/rlrmp/adversary.py` line 206). For the gate experiment, SISU=1 on all trials (single canonical reach).\n- **Per-replicate**: one ε array per controller replicate, matching the existing vmap layout (Codex Q7 resolution: per-replicate adversaries are fine for training; the *held-out audit* is where multiple independent adversaries against a frozen controller live).\n- **Batch structure**: same ε across the batch dim. The gate is a single canonical reach (Codex Q-batch resolution); mixed targets are Bridge 2.\n\n\n`FullStateAdditivePerturb` in `feedbax/intervene/intervene.py` (companion to `DynamicsMatrixPerturb` line 171+ and `FixedField` line 138+). MUST be a **discrete state update** implementing `x_{t+1} = A x_t + B u_t + ε_t`, NOT a force/dynamics perturbation. This is what makes the game match the Riccati's analytical setup.\n\n- Derives from `Component`, hooks after `Mechanics` steps.\n- Mutates all augmented state leaves (effector + integrator + lag buffer per the state-map).\n- Parameter type: `FullStateAdditivePerturbParams(InterventionParams)` — companion to `DynamicsMatrixPerturbParams` (line 67), with `active`, `scale`, and `epsilon_t: Float[Array, \"n\"]` (the per-step ε slice).\n- Wired via `PLANT_INTERVENOR_LABEL` swap pattern.\n\nThe feedbax-side change is in-scope for this issue per CLAUDE.md's \"near-integration with feedbax\" rule. Lands as a feature branch in feedbax, derived from `develop`.\n\n\nSame adversary class, fresh random init, against a frozen controller. PGD with `{5, 20, 50}` steps and 5 independent restarts per step-count. Used in Phase 3's robustness-match criterion and as the multi-adversary protocol (Codex Q7).\n\n\n`--adversary-type full_state_epsilon` on the new entry-point script (see Phase 2).\n\n---\n\n\nCodex Q3 resolution: a new entry-point script `scripts/train_round_trip.py` that **reuses library training primitives** from `rlrmp.train.minimax`. **Do not** force `train_minimax.py` to grow a `cs_faithful` mode — that pollutes the production CLI for a one-off matched experiment.\n\n- `scripts/train_round_trip.py`: cross-cutting CLI entry-point (stays in `scripts/` per CLAUDE.md script-placement rules).\n- Builds the cs_faithful task directly (k=0.1, τ=0.066, n_steps=60, hold-free, no go-cue, no catch trials, single canonical reach).\n- Wires the `FullStateEpsilonAdversary` via the new feedbax intervenor.\n- Dispatches `--hidden-type {linear, gru}`.\n- Reuses the fused PGD inner-loop from `train_minimax.py` (lines 1069+) via `rlrmp.train.minimax` library primitives — sibling-script imports between two files under `scripts/` are forbidden per CLAUDE.md, so any shared primitives needed by both entry-points must be promoted to `src/rlrmp/train/minimax.py` in the same auth request.\n\n**Information-structure constraint** (Codex risk #2): the trained controller MUST have the same observation / state access as the Riccati target. The Riccati is full-state feedback on the 48D augmented state. If the trained linear controller sees a different observation stream (e.g. only the physical 8D state, or a sensor-delayed observation), K-mismatch is expected and uninterpretable. Decision: **expose the full 48D augmented state to the linear controller** (and likewise to the GRU in Phase 4), matching the Riccati's information structure. Document this in `feedbax_state_map.md`.\n\n---\n\n\nIssue child: `89891ab` is the held-out audit folded into this phase.\n\n\n- **Model**: `--hidden-type linear` (LTV regulator `u_t = -K_t · x_t` for a time-varying gain).\n- **n_replicates**: 5 (matches production default; minimum for bimodality clustering per `daa48c8`).\n- **Warmup**: train without adversary for ~2000 batches against the matched cs_faithful task with ε=0. Verify the warmed-up regulator converges close to the analytical LQR (γ → ∞) Riccati K_t. **This is its own sub-gate** (criterion ii below).\n- **Adversarial phase**: switch to `FullStateEpsilonAdversary`, 8000 batches, PGD inner-step = 5 (default). After Phase-3 success, run the PGD step-count sweep `{5, 20, 50}` × 5 restarts on the frozen trained controller, comparing held-out adversary loss to trained adversary loss (`89891ab` audit).\n\n\nAll five must pass for the gate to succeed. Predeclare tolerances before training launches. Tolerances are placeholders pending Phase 0.5 numbers; refine when the analytical artifacts land.\n\n1. **K match**: `‖K_trained − K_H∞‖_F / ‖K_H∞‖_F \u003c τ_K`. Predeclared tolerance e.g. τ_K = 0.10 (10% relative Frobenius). Tighter if numerically stable.\n2. **LQR warmup sanity**: warmup-only K_warmup matches analytical LQR K* (γ → ∞) within `τ_LQR = 0.10`. Confirms SGD is finding the LQ minimum before adversarial training perturbs it. Failure here means the training pipeline is broken independent of the adversary.\n3. **Nominal trajectory match**: peak v_fwd, time-to-peak, terminal position error, and cost time-course (`x_t^T Q_t x_t` + `u_t^T R u_t`) all within predeclared tolerances of analytical H∞ trajectory. Predeclared: ±5% peak v_fwd, ±5% time-to-peak, ±2 mm terminal error.\n4. **Robustness match**: held-out full-state ε loss and induced full-state ε gain `γ_net(K_trained)` close to analytical H∞ value. Predeclared: `|γ_net(K_trained) − γ*(K_H∞)| / γ*(K_H∞) \u003c 0.10`.\n5. **Δv match**: trained Δv within absolute band `±2 pp` of the chosen-γ analytical Δv (e.g. analytical = +7.5% → trained ∈ [+5.5%, +9.5%]). This is much tighter than v1's \"\u003e +1%\" sign test, which Codex correctly identified as too loose.\n\n**Overshoot fail**: large positive Δv (e.g. \u003e +30%) with poor K-match or poor gain-match is **failure**, not partial success. The \"+30%\" line in v1 stays.\n\n\n| Mode | Diagnosis | Resolution |\n|---|---|---|\n| K mismatch + Δv mismatch + nominal off | Pipeline is not the H∞ game (Codex risk #1 or #2 active: state-map wrong, or information-structure wrong) | Stop. Re-audit Phase 0.5 / Phase 1 state-map. New follow-up issue tagged blocker. |\n| K mismatch only (Δv \u0026 nominal OK) | Possibly equivalent policy representation; check `K_trained = T K_H∞ T^{-1}` for some change of basis | Allow if explainable; otherwise treat as Mode 1. |\n| LQR warmup sanity fails | SGD not finding LQ minimum. Training-side bug (optimiser, init, data pipeline) | Diagnose before launching adversarial phase. |\n| Trained Δv \u003e +30% (overshoot) | Adversary is finding worst-case but K is overshooting OR PGD not converging | Run held-out audit (`89891ab`). If held-out loss \u003e trained loss \u003e 20%, PGD too weak → re-train at PGD = 50. Otherwise Mode 1. |\n| Held-out adversary loss ≫ trained loss | Trained adversary was not worst-case | Re-train at PGD = 50 inner steps with multi-restart. |\n| All gates pass | → Phase 4. |\n\n---\n\n\n**Only after Phase 3 passes.** If Phase 3 fails any gate, do not launch Phase 4; diagnose Phase 3 instead.\n\n\n- **Model**: `--hidden-type gru`, `hidden_size=180`, `population_structure` default (matches production).\n- **n_replicates**: 5.\n- **Training schedule**: identical to Phase 3 — same plant, same cost, same adversary, same budget, same observation access. Architecture is the *only* axis varying.\n- **Warmup**: 2000 batches without ε, then 8000 with full adversary.\n\n\nCodex was explicit that Phase 4 must enumerate all three outcomes, not defer to post-experiment synthesis — otherwise outcome (a) gets misreported as a plain success.\n\n**Outcome (a): GRU dissociates** — preserved induced-gain modulation under held-out ε but flat nominal Δv (or qualitatively below the linear regulator's Δv). The RNN is more tracker-like than the human behavioural phenotype. The full-state ε game *can* be solved with decoupled FF/FB by a parameterisation rich enough to do so; humans (per cs2019) don't, and the linear regulator structurally can't. **Outcome (a) is the substantive scientific finding** if it occurs — humans are leaving optimal control on the table because their effective parameterisation is regulator-like. Follow-up: `0bbd1ef` Path 1 vs Path 2 (see Path-(a) Contingency below).\n\n**Outcome (b): GRU couples** — recovers the linear regulator's +Δv signature with held-out gain inflation. The +Δv signature is a property of the *training game* (full-state ε H∞), not of the parameterisation. Codex's decoupling hypothesis (the synthesis's Q3 reframe) is wrong. Humans showing +Δv is consistent with adopting the matched game. Follow-up: `0c95d6b` to investigate *how* the GRU implements the coupled solution (subject to the spec-update caveat below).\n\n**Outcome (c): GRU partially couples** — quantitative middle ground, modest +Δv reduction with some gain modulation. Coupling is a quantitative property of \"how much you couple,\" not a binary. Report where the GRU lands on the robustness-vs-nominal-speed frontier relative to the linear regulator and the analytical Riccati.\n\n**Outcome (d, distinct from a/b/c): GRU collapses** — null Δv AND null held-out gain inflation. GRU is dropping the adversary signal entirely. Diagnose training (PGD too weak, exploration collapsed, etc.); not a scientific outcome.\n\n\nIf outcome (a) occurs: two paths to a human-comparable interpretability target:\n\n- **Path 1 (biomechanical, scientifically preferred per Codex `355ff46`)**: add nonlinear damping → two-link arm (`ac06736`) → muscles. Test whether realistic plant suppresses decoupling. If decoupling disappears at some specific rung of the ladder, that's diagnostic of why humans don't decouple.\n- **Path 2 (architectural restriction, scientific shortcut)**: stateless feedback, information bottleneck, teacher distillation (`db35426`), or aux loss. Weaker scientific result — if we restrict the GRU to a class that can't decouple, it must match the human signature by construction.\n\nCodex's stated preference: *\"if outcome (a) happens, the next best step is not immediately 'make the GRU match humans'; it is to identify which real constraint prevents decoupling.\"* I agree: Path 1 produces a falsifiable claim about human motor control (some specific biomechanical complication suppresses decoupling); Path 2 produces a circular claim (we built a GRU that approximates the Riccati, here is how). Path 2 may still be a useful tool — e.g. distilling the Riccati's coupled solution into a GRU is a capacity check, independent of the path question — but it is not a substitute for Path 1.\n\n**The contingency planning itself stays on the synthesis issue `0b1f109` and on `0bbd1ef`.** Phase 4 of this plan only commits to enumerating the three outcomes and pointing at the contingency — it does not pre-commit to which path runs first if outcome (a) occurs.\n\n\n`0c95d6b` (Tier 1 GRU affine decomposition) currently specifies measuring K_local on \"a clean undisturbed reach.\" This is degenerate — on x_nom(t) with no perturbation the feedback-correction signal is zero by construction. The decomposition must be measured under **standardised small perturbations** (impulse responses, sensory step changes, motor noise injection) where the feedback-correction signal is non-zero. Before opening `0c95d6b` for follow-up work after Phase 4, update its spec to require:\n\n(i) standardised perturbation protocol;\n(ii) measurement of K_local(t) via Jacobians along *perturbed* trajectories;\n(iii) decomposition of u into ‖u_nom‖² (on x_nom) and ‖u_correction‖² (on x_perturbed − x_nom).\n\nComment on `0c95d6b` with this requirement when opening the follow-up. (This is the same caveat as v1; preserved.)\n\n---\n\n\nFor both arms (linear and GRU), per replicate, compute:\n\n| Signature | Definition | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Δv (nominal) | Peak forward velocity on the 15 cm forward reach, ε=0, vs the matched baseline | `rlrmp.eval.kinematics` |\n| Δv (held-out ε) | Peak forward velocity under independent strong-adversary search | New: Phase 1 held-out audit infrastructure |\n| Nominal trajectory profile | x_nom(t) full profile, not just peak | `rlrmp.eval.kinematics` |\n| K_local time series | Local feedback Jacobian along x_nom(t); for the linear arm this *is* K_t | `rlrmp.analysis.induced_gain` Jacobian path |\n| Feedback-gain step-response | Impulse perturbation at trial midpoint, peak corrective force / peak velocity deflection | New code: extends `rlrmp.eval.pert`-style pipeline |\n| Induced gain by channel | `additive_force`, `sensory_perturbation`, `structural_da`, and **NEW: `full_state_epsilon`** | `rlrmp.analysis.induced_gain` (extend `_W_CHANNELS`) |\n| Endpoint / lateral deviation | Terminal position error in fwd \u0026 lat axes | `rlrmp.eval.kinematics` |\n| Held-out adversary loss | Loss under strong independent adversary (PGD 50 × 5 restarts) | New: held-out adversary CLI helper |\n\n\nBoth baselines, with different roles:\n\n- **Analytical LQR (γ → ∞)** — the *mathematical* baseline. Used for the Riccati-match criterion (criteria 1, 2, 3, 5 in Phase 3 gate). The Δv \"match\" is against the chosen-γ analytical H∞ Δv relative to this LQR baseline.\n- **Trained warmup-only** — the *empirical* baseline. Used to check \"what SGD found without an adversary\" and to compute trained-vs-trained Δv. The gate requires consistency with the analytical baseline, not just relative-to-warmup Δv.\n\n\nPer CLAUDE.md plotting rules (`rlrmp.viz.profile_comparison_grid` with shared y-axes). Cluster replicates by `(Δv, final_loss, induced_gain_full_state_epsilon)` triple using `sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture(n_components=2)`. Report cluster means + per-replicate scatter; never the bare group mean (per `daa48c8`).\n\n\n- `rlrmp.analysis.replicate_clustering` (or similar) — small module exposing a function that takes a multi-signature DataFrame (one row per replicate) and returns cluster labels + per-cluster summary. Capability-named per CLAUDE.md script-placement; reusable across all future replicate-based reporting; lives in the library, not in the experiment script.\n- Extension to `induced_gain.py`: add `W_FULL_STATE_EPSILON = \"full_state_epsilon\"` and the corresponding `Bw_raw` construction in `linearise_trajectory` (full-state additive ⇒ `B_w = I_n` at every timestep). Update `_W_CHANNELS`.\n\n---\n\n\nPhase 4 produces the cs_faithful GRU (or a failure-mode diagnosis). It does NOT produce the interpretability target — that is on a delayed-reach version on the production plant. The propagation is not a single gate; it is a **5-stage chain of consistency checks**, each adding one complication, with the cs_faithful signatures as the anchor.\n\n| Stage | Plant | Task | Adversary | Analytical anchor | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Gate (this issue)** | cs_faithful (k=0.1, τ=0.066) | hold-free, single canonical reach | full-state ε over whole rollout | cs_faithful Riccati | Certify the training pipeline solves the H∞ game |\n| **Bridge 1: plant** | production (k=10, τ=0.05) | hold-free, single canonical reach | full-state ε over whole rollout | new Riccati at production plant | Verify pipeline still solves the H∞ game when plant params shift 100× in k |\n| **Bridge 2: targets** | production | hold-free, center-out 8-direction | full-state ε, per-trial | cs_faithful Riccati per-direction (if tractable for LTI) | Verify generalisation across reach directions |\n| **Bridge 3: delayed-reach** | production | hold + target_on + movement epochs | ε **only in movement epoch** | cs_faithful Riccati on movement epoch only | Add preparation/hold structure; check movement-epoch signatures match Bridge 2 |\n| **Interpretability** | production | delayed-reach | as above | (none direct) | Dynamical-systems analysis on Bridge 3 GRU (`0c95d6b` lives here) |\n\n**Each bridge is a consistency check against the prior step's signatures, not a fresh gate.** The cs_faithful gate certifies the *training pipeline*; the bridges propagate to the eventual interpretability target without re-deriving a fresh analytical Riccati at every step (Bridge 1 is the exception — fresh Riccati at production plant).\n\n**Critical constraint for Bridge 3**: the ε adversary MUST be **epoch-gated** — active only during the movement epoch, via `epoch_mask(\"movement\")` from `TrialTimeline`. Without this, the adversary perturbs preparation state too, which is a different (probably ill-defined analytically) game. The intervenor must honour epoch masks; this is a feedbax-side requirement for Bridge 3 implementation.\n\n**Asymmetric anchoring**: the gate certifies *movement-epoch H∞ behaviour*. The hold-period dynamics are anchored only to b399efc's empirical baseline (movement_ramp schedule, prego penalties), not to any analytical target. Both are interesting; they're interpreted against different references.\n\n**Two of v1's OPEN questions are resolved by being deferred to bridges**, not by being answered now:\n\n- v1 Q1 (production plant): Bridge 1. Filed as a separate follow-up issue *after* the gate passes; not Phase 1b of this issue.\n- v1 Q4 (delayed-reach hold/catch): Bridge 3. Same deferral.\n\n---\n\n\n1. **`FullStateAdditivePerturb` state-map (Codex risk #1)** — blocker-level. The 48D delay-augmented state may not be cleanly mutable through a feedbax intervenor. **Block Phase 1 launch until the state-map note + regression test exist and pass.** If delay-buffer states cannot be materialised, fallback is to use the 8-state plant (`disturbance_integrator=True, delay_steps=0`) and re-derive the analytical target in Phase 0.5 — different Δv number (~+2% pre-9a0558e versus ~+7.5% post-lift), but a cleanly-implementable game.\n2. **Information-structure parity (Codex risk #2)** — the trained controller and the Riccati target must see the same state/observation. Forcing the linear/GRU to see the full 48D augmented state may interact non-trivially with feedbax's sensor-delay machinery. Verify in the state-map note.\n3. **ε metric / units (Codex risk #3)** — Euclidean norm over 48 augmented-state coordinates must match the Riccati's metric. Verify scaling consistency across `cs_eq15_cost_schedule`, feedbax `MechanicsState` leaves, and the PGD projection.\n4. **Bridge 1 non-triviality** — cs_faithful k=0.1 vs production k=10 is a 100× damping change. The gate-pass at cs_faithful does NOT automatically extend to production plant; Bridge 1 needs its own Riccati re-derivation and consistency check. Codex's deferral is the right call but Bridge 1 is non-trivial work, not a rubber stamp.\n5. **PGD weakness** — if held-out adversary loss substantially exceeds trained loss, the trained adversary was not worst-case and downstream Δv interpretation is unreliable. The `89891ab` audit at PGD ∈ {5, 20, 50} × 5 restarts is built into Phase 3, but pre-flight PGD calibration on the linear arm may be wanted before the GRU arm is launched.\n6. **Bimodal-replicate masking** — group means hide qualitatively different solutions. The `daa48c8` clustering protocol (Phase 5) is mandatory.\n\n---\n\n\nv2 resolves 5 of v1's 7 OPEN questions in-plan (Q2, Q3, Q5, Q6, Q7 per Codex `355ff46`) and defers 2 to the bridging chain (Q1 → Bridge 1, Q4 → Bridge 3). Two new residual decisions remain:\n\n1. **OPEN — Predeclared tolerances for the multi-criterion gate.** The placeholders above (τ_K = 0.10, ±2pp on Δv, ±5% on peak v_fwd, ±5% on time-to-peak, ±2 mm terminal error, γ-match within 10%) need refinement once Phase 0.5 produces the actual analytical numbers and we know the noise floor on the trained linear arm's SGD optimisation. **Decision needed after Phase 0.5 lands, before Phase 3 training launches.** Falls naturally out of Phase 0.5 deliverables — should not block plan acceptance.\n\n2. **OPEN — Fallback if delay-buffer states cannot be materialised in feedbax.** If the regression test for the 48D state-map fails because the lag chain is implicit in feedbax's simulator rather than carried as explicit state, the choice is: (a) materialise the lag chain in feedbax (substantial feedbax-side work, may break other things); (b) fall back to the 8-state form (`disturbance_integrator=True, delay_steps=0`) and re-derive Phase 0.5 — analytical Δv drops from ~+7.5% to ~+2%, smaller signal but cleaner game; (c) build the round-trip with the lag chain implicit and accept a mismatch in `B_w` (then the trained controller's K mismatch with the analytical K_H∞ is expected and uninterpretable — this is option (c) only as a last resort, basically a re-spec of the gate). **Recommend (b) as the default fallback** — preserves the matched-game property at the cost of a smaller analytical Δv signal. **Decision needed during Phase 1 state-map work.**\n\n---\n\n\n- **Parent / synthesis frame**: `0b1f109` (synthesis) + comments `0cbb19f` (Eq 9 → 10 math), `0dbf19f` (broad-defense framing), `08b41df` (three-outcome decision tree), `0bbd1ef` (Path 1 / Path 2), `01b512f` (bridging chain)\n- **Codex critique that drove this revision**: `35f64be` comment `355ff46`\n- **Superseded predecessor**: `35f64be` (v1 plan; kept open as historical record)\n- **Implementation child**: `020a65b` (full-state ε adversary class — Phase 1)\n- **Bundled prerequisites (folded)**: `89891ab` (PGD sweep — Phase 1 + Phase 3 held-out audit), `6ec6b19` (cost schedule — folded into Phase 0.5), `daa48c8` (bimodal-replicate analysis — Phase 5 clustering)\n- **Pre-compute audit (BLOCKING)**: `b6084c7`\n- **Phase umbrella**: `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase)\n- **Decision records (constraints, applies to Bridge 1 not the gate)**: `a04711e` (k=10 damping — production plant), `08c49e3` (τ=50ms — production plant)\n- **Reference flavor-B numbers**: `c723082` comment `c87b273` (mean Δv ≈ −25%, bimodal +40% / −25% split)\n- **Matrix-winner warmup reference**: `b399efc` (`movement_ramp__power6_dur80`)\n- **Riccati infrastructure**: `src/rlrmp/analysis/hinf_riccati.py` — `cs_faithful_pointmass` (line 468), `cs_eq15_cost_schedule` (line 1192), `apply_delay_distribution_to_schedule` (line 791), `solve_hinf_riccati` (line 1425), `find_gamma_star` (l